<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 8:14<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27da1d50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>8.</label.designator><headtext>Relevancy</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71ff010682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>8:14.</label.designator><headtext>Similar transactions—Punitive damages</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1991206340" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d658de27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>City of Monroe v. Jordan</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic46679c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] evidence that defendant&apos;s truck driver had been involved in two previous traffic accidents was relevant and admissible on the issue of punitive damages because a bad driving record indicated willfulness or a reckless disregard for consequences.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Likewise, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1994094944" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d669f527fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Holt v. Grinnell</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic46679c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] evidence that defendant has pled guilty to driving under the influence prior to or after the incident is relevant to the issue of punitive damages in a case involving defendant driving under the influence.<eos/><page no="249"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Injuries caused to a dentist&apos;s previous patients, resulting from his continuation of the same treatment used for the plaintiff, was admissible on the issue of punitive damages.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic46679c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Evidence of other injuries involving the same product is admissible and relevant to the issue of notice of defect and punitive damages.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic466a0d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Evidence of a defendant&apos;s sexually inappropriate behavior to another individual was admissible on issue of punitive damages in a case alleging sexual harassment.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic466a0d17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1998061925" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d68e9427fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Webster v. Boyett</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic466a0d27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court reversed the decision of the Court of Appeals which held that evidence of a previous conviction for driving under the influence was admissible to show both whether defendant is liable for punitive damages and the amount of punitive damages. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Supreme Court stated that judges should use their discretion, not a bright line test, for determining the admissibility of prior or subsequent acts and should exclude relevant evidence only if its probative value is substantially outweighed by the risk that its admission will confuse the issue, mislead the jury, or create substantial danger of undue prejudice.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic466a0d37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic46679c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1991206340" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d6603127fc011ea988285db8533e975">City of Monroe v. Jordan, 201 Ga. App. 332, 411 S.E.2d 511 (1991)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="2003677202" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d6603157fc011ea988285db8533e975">Sheriff v. State, 277 Ga. 182, 587 S.E.2d 27 (2003)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic46679c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1994094944" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d66ed727fc011ea988285db8533e975">Holt v. Grinnell, 212 Ga. App. 520, 441 S.E.2d 874 (1994)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="249"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic46679c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1979128001" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d6762a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Gunthorpe v. Daniels, 150 Ga. App. 113, 257 S.E.2d 199 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic466a0d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1998076280" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d67d7d27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Barger v. Garden Way, Inc., 231 Ga. App. 723, 729, 499 S.E.2d 737 (1998)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic466a0d17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1999078387" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d684d027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Troncalli v. Jones, 237 Ga. App. 10, 514 S.E.2d 478 (1999)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic466a0d27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1998061925" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2d6910527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Webster v. Boyett, 269 Ga. 191, 496 S.E.2d 459 (1998)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic466a0d37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017139" w-serial-number="1998061925" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" w-pinpoint-page="463" ID="I2d69d3a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Webster v. Boyett, 269 Ga. 191, 195, 496 S.E.2d 459, 463 (1998)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadat